where min_sal=1 or max_sal=1

text:
Question 1  -- Solution 2: Using window function.

select user_id, user_name, email
from (
select *,
row_number() over (partition by user_name order by user_id) as rn
from users u
order by user_id) x
where x.rn <> 1;

text:
I don't like the use of the partition to solve this particular problem as it won't work on databases that have not implemented the windowed functions.
Much better and shorter would using the HAVING clause like

SELECT * 
FROM Users 
WHERE User_id IN (SELECT User_id FROM Users GROUP BY user_id HAVING Count(*) > 1)

text: Sql delevoper means what and sql sever means what could u explain
author: Asha Ashu

text:
SQL is a programming language which is used to interact with any RDBMS

SQL Developer is a tool (an IDE) which is used to write your SQL code by connecting to the RDBMS. This tool is from Oracle but there are many other tools as well to connect to different RDBMS

SQL Server is a RDBMS. It is called Microsoft SQL server. There are several other RDBMS as well like MySQL, Oracle, PostgreSQL etc.

3. Write a SQL query to display only the details of employees who either earn the highest salary or the lowest salary in each department from the employee table:
WITH Dep_min_max as (select dept_name, min(salary) [Min],max(salary) [Max] from employee group by dept_name)
SELECT e.* , d.[Max] , d.[Min] 
from Employee e join Dep_min_max d on e.dept_name = d.dept_name
where e.Salary in (d.[Min],d.[Max]);
==================================================

¬†@BAIRI ROHITH REDDY¬† I think this is because I am using a view instead of the actual table. I believe the reason TechTFQ does not have that problem because he created the table directly and is running the query on it directly. In practice, there will be very few tables that you can actually access directly and without a view inbetween. I suppose the work around is to create a temp table, push the the data into and then run the query against that. 

I'd like to see what the "unless TOP, OFFSET or FOR XML is also specified". Maybe that can make it work even for views.

text:
Alternate Solution for Problem 3:

select x.emp_id,x.emp_name,x.dept_name,x.salary from 
(select e.*,
rank() over (partition by dept_name order by salary desc) as rnk_max,
rank() over (partition by dept_name order by salary asc) as rnk_min
from employee e)x
where x.rnk_max==1 OR x.rnk_min==1
order by x.dept_name,x.salary;

P.S: I really didn't want to use a join lol

text:
So we need to interchange the column values for adjacent rows.

So if SQL is processing odd record (odd numbers such as 1, 3, etc and knowing that the first record will always be an odd) then fetch the column value stored in the very next even record using the lead function.

If SQL is processing even record (even numbers such as 2, 4, etc) then fetch the column value stored in the previous odd record using the lag function.

In order to identify if a record is odd or even we use the ID field and check using the modulus symbol "%". It can be used to return the remainder when you divide two numbers. Any number%2 will return 0 if the number is even. It will return 1 if number is odd. Once we identify if ID (which in this case represents a row in the table) is even or odd, we can either apply LEAD or LAG function to get the desired column value.

For the last record, if it is odd then it wont be able to fetch the adjacent even number hence the LEAD function will return the default value which is NULL. We can change this default value by passing an third argument in LEAD function (which in our case should be a same column value).

Hope the explanation helps. Do try
